50|$|A photoplethysmogram (PPG) is an {{optically}} obtained plethysmogram, a {{volumetric measurement}} of an organ. A PPG is often obtained {{by using a}} <b>pulse</b> <b>oximeter</b> which illuminates the skin and measures changes in light absorption. A conventional <b>pulse</b> <b>oximeter</b> monitors the perfusion of blood to the dermis and subcutaneous tissue of the skin.With each cardiac cycle the heart pumps blood to the periphery. Even though this pressure pulse is somewhat damped {{by the time it}} reaches the skin, it is enough to distend the arteries and arterioles in the subcutaneous tissue. If the <b>pulse</b> <b>oximeter</b> is attached without compressing the skin, a pressure pulse can also be seen from the venous plexus, as a small secondary peak.|$|E
